Languages are now considered to be on a par with the STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of independent schools and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 found that 17 per cent of employers cited language skills as a barrier to filling jobs.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly indispensable for preparing young people for their future careers.
The potential for employment requiring language skills is increasing, and these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career path someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future, thanks to this kind of lifelong competence.
The fact that he can communicate directly with people from foreign countries will enable him to get ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75 per cent of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15 per cent, was French.
For this reason, investing in language education is important for today's children.
If they know several languages, especially those of developing economies, they will be better equipped to have better opportunities to find quality employment.
In Scotland, different languages will be taught in different schools.
Some centres will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the United Kingdom by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the child &apos; s interests, independent schools always offered a choice of several languages taught by specialist staff.
Scotland &apos; s independent schools are dedicated to providing an environment of learning that prepares children and equips them with the skills to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At present, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be vital to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages must be considered &quot; competencies for international communication &quot;.
Independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It must be done.
