The National Trust spies on the secret lives of bats
This new research, which has been carried out in a Highland Scottish state, seeks to discover how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
It is hoped that what is learned will shed more light on the behaviour of the only flying mammals and help to guide future conservation efforts.
The study, carried out by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common and soprano pipistrelle bats, as well as Daubenton's bat and long-eared bats of Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in strategic locations on the property to track bat activity during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
Experts will analyse the sounds picked up in the recordings to determine the frequency of calls by bats and the species that make them.
A habitat report and map will then be produced to provide a detailed picture of the environment and its behaviour.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation adviser for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how they use them.
This information will identify the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of grasslands and how forests should be managed for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined considerably in the last century.
They are under threat from construction and development that affects their nests and the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and electrical wiring can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticides and other chemicals in building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind,
Instead, because of its nocturnal hunting habits, its ears are more useful than its eyes in achieving its goal.
They use sophisticated ecolocation techniques to locate ants and obstacles on their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes the issue of bats very seriously.
It has 10 trained experts who regularly carry out surveys, nest inspections and, on occasion, rescue operations.
The organization has even opened the first and only reserve dedicated to bats in Scotland in the state of Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, which is the home of eight of the ten species of bat in Scotland.
The owner, David Thompson, says it is the ideal territory for them.
Here at Threave we have a fantastic area for bats," he said.
We have old buildings, many veteran trees and all the right habitat.
However, there is still much that is unknown about bats, and the work that we are doing here and elsewhere will help us to understand better what they need to develop."
It stresses the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance work on the property, as a colony of breeding bats could be unintentionally destroyed and 400 females and juveniles could be killed, which would wipe out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their colonies.
The Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, Elisabeth Ferrell, has encouraged the public to get involved.
He said: "We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species on which we do not know how their populations are evolving."
