The trade war between the United States and China could benefit Beijing
The first salvos of the trade war between the United States and China were deafening, and although there is still a long way to go before the battle is over, a rupture between the countries could benefit Beijing, experts say.
Donald Trump, the US President, issued the first warning in early 2018 by placing tariffs on major Chinese exports, such as solar panels, steel and aluminium.
The most significant escalation took place this week with new tariffs on $200 billion (£150 billion) of goods, which will tax half of the goods that come into the United States from China.
On each occasion, Beijing has retaliated in kind, recently imposing tariffs of 5 to 10 per cent on American products worth $60 billion.
China has committed itself to matching the United States' attacks, and it is unlikely that the world's second largest economy will soon ease up.
To back down from Washington would mean giving in to demands, but publicly submitting to the United States would be too shameful for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
Even so, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards right, the United States &apos; trade war could help China in the long run by reducing the interdependence between the two economies.
The fact that a rapid political decision in Washington or Beijing could set the stage for a crash landing in the economy in either country is, in fact, far more dangerous than has been recognized by observers so far, said Abigail Grace, associate fellow focused on Asia for the Center for New American Security.
Syria ready to receive refugees, says Foreign Minister
Syria asserts that it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and requests assistance in rebuilding a country devastated by a war that has lasted more than seven years.
In a speech to the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that the conditions in the country were improving.
The situation on the ground is today more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism.
The Government was continuing to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists in an effort to restore normalcy.
All the conditions for the voluntary return of refugees who had been forced to leave their country because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures that had affected their daily lives and livelihoods were in place.
The UN estimates that since the war began in 2011, more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country.
There are another six million people in the country who still need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem acknowledged that the Syrian regime would welcome assistance in rebuilding the devastated country.
But he also emphasized that he would not accept conditional aid or aid from countries that had promoted the insurgency.
