Red tide update: Concentrations decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The new report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (FFWC) shows a general decrease in red tide concentrations in areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to FWC, irregular bloom conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The bloom extends approximately 130 miles along the shoreline from Pinellas County north to Lee County south.
Irregular parcels can be found as far as 10 miles from the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer than last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Pasco County.
During the past week, medium concentrations have been reported in Pinellas County and on its coast, low to moderate concentrations have been reported on the coast of Hillsborough County, deep concentrations to high concentrations have been reported in Manatee County, deep concentrations to high concentrations have been reported in Sarasota County and its coast, moderate to high concentrations have been reported in Charlotte County, moderate to high concentrations have been reported in Lee County and its coast, and low concentrations have been reported in Collier County.
Reports of respiratory irritation continue in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
There were no reports of respiratory irritation in the north-west of Florida during the past week.
